SIMPLE: transpose
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Transpose
<hw>Trans*pose"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Transposed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Transposing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>transposer</ets>; pref. <ets>trans-</ets> (L. <ets>trans</ets>
across) + <ets>poser</ets> to put. See <er>Pose</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To change the place or order of; to substitute one
for the other of; to exchange, in respect of position; <as>as, to
<ex>transpose</ex> letters, words, or propositions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To change; to transform; to invert.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Things base and vile, holding no quantity,⟦br⟧
Love can <qex>transpose</qex> to form and dignity.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Alg.)</fld> <def>To bring, as any term of an
equation, from one side over to the other, without destroying the
equation; thus, if <mathex>a + b = c</mathex>, and we make <mathex>a = c
- b</mathex>, then <it>b</it> is said to be
<xex>transposed</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>To change the natural order of,
as words.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To change the key of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Transposer</ent>⟦br⟧
